</p>
<p><b>Independence of 
judges and 
lawyers;  
Terrorism;  
Torture;   
</b> 
</p>
<p>Alleged torture during interrogation to coerce a confession used to incriminate and 
substantiate a conviction for participating in terrorist activities in Saudi Arabia; 
alleged prolonged solitary confinement. According to the information received, on 11 
June 2003, Mr Ahmed Abu Ali was arrested in Medina, Saudi Arabia upon the request 
of the United States, beaten and whipped in prison until he confessed to being a 
member of an Al-Qaeda cell. He was transferred to Riyadh where he was allegedly 
subjected to solitary confinement, and sleep deprivation. Subsequently, he was 
reportedly transferred to the United States where the confessions he made during the 
interrogations in Saudi Arabia were used against him as the basis for a conviction for 
material support to the Al Qaeda network. Mr Ali&#8217;s health condition is deteriorating 
while he is serving a sentence to life imprisonment without parole in solitary 
confinement at the United States Penitentiary, Administrative Maximum Facility 
(ADX).  
</p>
